'''Head of navigation''' is the farthest point above the mouth of a [[river]] that can be navigated by [[ship]]s.  Determining the head of navigation can be subjective on many streams, as this point may vary greatly with the size of the ship being contemplated for navigation and the seasonal water level.  On others, it is quite objective, being caused by a [[waterfall]] or a [[dam]] without navigation [[Canal lock|locks]]. Several rivers in a region may have their heads of navigation along a line called the [[Fall line]]. 

