{{Infobox language family |name=Mangbutu–Lese |altname=Mangbutu–Efe |region=[[Democratic Republic of Congo]], [[Uganda]] |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Central Sudanic]] |fam3=Eastern |child1=[[Mangbutu language|Mangbutu]] |child2=[[Mvuba language|Mvuba]] |child3=[[Ndo language|Ndo]] (Membitu) |child4=[[Mamvu language|Mamvu]] |child5=[[Lese language|Lese]] (incl. Efe) |child6=?[[Bendi language (Sudanic)|Bendi]] |glotto=memb1239 |glottorefname=Membi–Mangbutu–Efe }}
The '''Mangbutu–Lese languages''' of the [[Central Sudanic languages|Central Sudanic language family]], also known as '''Mangbutu–Efe''' or simply '''Mangbutu''' (e.g. Starostin 2016), are a cluster of closely related languages spoken in the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] and [[Uganda]].
The languages are: :[[Mangbutu language|Mangbutu]], [[Mvuba language|Mvuba]], [[Ndo language|Ndo]], [[Mamvu language|Mamvu]], [[Lese language|Lese]], [[Bendi language (Sudanic)|Bendi]]. Efe (the language of the [[Efe people|Efe]] Pygmies) is often counted as another, but appears to be a dialect of Lese. Ndo (Membitu) is the most populous language and is spoken by a [[caste]] of blacksmiths.
